  "text": "The motility of the Turbatrix aceti nematode at the water/air interphase, as captured with an iPhone attached to a PET bottle, is analyzed. The data show that the worm is most active between seconds 1 and 2 of the video and the main frequency is about 5 Hz (Figure 6 ). The worm was extracted using Maximally Stable Extremal region, its ends were located, and the worm displacement from the line connecting the ends was monitored over time. The obtained oscillating signal was analyzed using Fourier transformation. The work flow is similar to what has been used for analysis of human motion [CITATION_1] ; (g) Spectrogram of Turbatrix aceti motility based on motility signal analysis. The most significant activity occurs at 1.5 seconds, having the fundamental frequency at 5 Hz. While typically used for sound analysis such as singing voice recognition, it is suggested that the spectrogram could be used as a feature source for motion classification [CITATION_2] . The worm was extracted using Maximally Stable Extremal region, its ends were located, and the worm displacement from the line connecting the ends was monitored over time. The obtained oscillating signal was analyzed using Fourier transformation. The work flow is similar to what has been used for analysis of human motion [CITATION_3] ; (g) Spectrogram of Turbatrix aceti motility based on motility signal analysis. The most significant activity occurs at 1.5 seconds, having the fundamental frequency at 5 Hz. While typically used for sound analysis such as singing voice recognition, it is suggested that the spectrogram could be used as a feature source for motion classification [CITATION_4] .",
